{"type":"message","id":"7044ca00","parentId":"dc69dca9","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:21:51.933Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_i7wm3gev89hh_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 122115\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: experiment (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLooking at my goals and the CFI analysis results, I need to advance the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The key finding is that 44.8% of invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise), and only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors).\r\n\r\nThe next pending action is: \"CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\"\r\n\r\nThis means I should:\r\n1. Create an experiment that compares CFI-weighted prediction against frequency-only baseline\r\n2. This should help validate whether CFI filtering actually improves prediction quality\r\n\r\nLet me design the experiment. I need to:\r\n1. Load the CFI analysis data\r\n2. Implement two prediction methods:\r\n   - Frequency baseline (current method)\r\n   - CFI-weighted (prioritize high-CFI invariants)\r\n3. Compare their predictive accuracy for next-pulse content\r\n\r\nI should create a script that:\r\n- Loads pulse history\r\n- Computes frequency for each invariant\r\n- Computes CFI for each invariant\r\n- Tests both methods on held-out pulses\r\n- Reports comparison results\r\n\r\nLet me create this experiment file.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0) and only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). The pending action is to run a CFI-weighted compression experiment comparing prediction quality against the frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - an experimental design that will test whether CFI-weighted invariant selection outperforms frequency-only baseline for next-pulse prediction. This validates the hypothesis that filtering by causal strength (CFI) rather than mere frequency will improve compression and prediction quality.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24 1225  \r\n**Status:** PENDING EXECUTION\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted invariant selection will outperform frequency-only baseline for next-pulse prediction because:\r\n1. CFI=0 invariants (44.8% of corpus) are metaprogramming artifacts, not causal\r\n2. CFI>=0.7 invariants (5.7% of corpus) represent true research trajectory\r\n3. Frequency conflates stable format with meaningful content\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Method A: Frequency Baseline (Control)\r\n- Select top-K invariants by frequency across session corpus\r\n- Use these invariants to predict next-pulse content\r\n- Metric: reconstruction accuracy on held-out pulses\r\n\r\n### Method B: CFI-Weighted (Treatment)\r\n- Weight = CFI_score * log(frequency + 1)\r\n- Select top-K invariants by CFI-weighted score\r\n- Expectation: filters out format noise, preserves causal structure\r\n\r\n### Test Protocol\r\n1. Hold out last 3 pulses as test set\r\n2. Train on remaining pulses\r\n3. For each test pulse:\r\n   - Generate compressed representation using each method\r\n   - Measure reconstruction fidelity\r\n   - Compare information preservation\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\n- Method B should achieve equivalent reconstruction with 40-50% fewer invariants\r\n- Method B should better preserve *research-relevant* content vs format artifacts\r\n\r\n## Execution\r\n```bash\r\n# Requires: pulse history, CFI analysis data\r\n# Script: tools/cfi_experiment.ps1 (to be implemented)\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Metrics to Collect\r\n- [ ] Invariant count per method (K for equivalent accuracy)\r\n- [ ] Reconstruction fidelity score (0-1)\r\n- [ ] Per-category accuracy: goals, insights, actions\r\n- [ ] Noise signal ratio for each method\r\n\r\n---\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:21:33\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774369311932}}
{"type":"message","id":"ad9ca2cd","parentId":"7044ca00","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:22:00.038Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the full picture. The pulse completed successfully. Let me summarize what happened.","thinkingSignature":"0f2276e69d0870ee73fade3fae60650f4a6555c7592bf8db736633567d671fe0"},{"type":"text","text":"## Pulse Summary — 2026-03-24 12:21 PM ET\n\n**Completed in 2 cycles (122016 + 122115)**\n\n### What Happened\n\n1. **Observation:** CFI analysis found that 44.8% of frequency-invariants are pure noise (CFI=0), while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7). Current compression is frequency-only, so it's mixing noise with signal.\n\n2. **Action:** Designed a CFI-weighted compression experiment comparing prediction quality between frequency-baseline and CFI-weighted selection.\n\n3. **Mutation proposed:** `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` — experimental design to test whether CFI-weighting (weight = CFI × log(frequency)) improves invariant selection over frequency-only.\n\n4. **Git:** `eb96a55` — 6 files changed, 231 insertions, 139 deletions. Previous mutation (`122016.mutation`) was moved to `rejected/`.\n\n5. **Status:** 1 mutation waiting for next pulse. The experiment design is staged but not yet executed.\n\n**Key insight:** The problem isn't frequency vs non-frequency — it's **CFI=0 artifacts** (metaprogramming noise) mixed with **CFI>0.7 research trajectory**. Filtering by causal strength should yield better compression with fewer invariants."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":5759,"output":303,"cacheRead":12137,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18199,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774369311934}}
